text: I thought salsa was just a dance until my chips got an unexpected workout.
Spencer Hastings from "Pretty Little Liars" is so determined, she could find a needle in a haystack even if the needle was just a rumor.
Ibiza is where you go to party all night and sleep all day, or as I call it, "reverse hibernation."
The film "Spencer" really showed Princess Diana's struggles, it's like the royal version of "The Blair Witch Project"—lots of running and crying in fancy clothes.
I told my clock it was doing a great job, but all it did was strike again.
I used a Spencer microscope and it was so old school, I expected to see tiny scholars in the petri dish.
I told my friend I sleep on a silk pillowcase to prevent wrinkles, but really, it's just my excuse for not ironing my face in the morning.
I walked El Camino to find myself, but all I found was blisters and a new appreciation for taxis.
My silk scarf is the perfect accessory; it can turn any outfit into a chokehold of elegance.
I asked a cardiologist to help me with my love life, but she said she only deals with real hearts, not broken ones.
I hit 'restore purchase' in my dating app, but it still couldn't find my sense of humor.
I bought silk flowers for my allergy-prone girlfriend; she said, "Achoo-sing wisely."
The Industrial Revolution really turned things around – before that, everyone was just spinning their wheels.
My poem's rhyme scheme was so bad, the last time it rhymed was by accident.
I heard about this heist plot where the thieves synchronized their watches, but they still couldn't steal extra time.
Refinishing antique furniture is the adult version of saying, "It's not old, it's vintage!"
I heard about a historic shipwreck at the reef, but when I visited, it was a wreck.
My 3D printer made a model of itself; I think it's getting narcissistic.
I told my friend I had a plan for a cultural shift, but he just changed the topic.
I bought a revolutionary kitchen gadget that's supposed to slice, dice, and overthrow the government, but it just ended up making julienne fries.
I thought I was part of a political ploy, but it turns out I just accidentally walked into a flash mob.
I asked my PlayStation for a weather update, and it said, "Greatness Awaits... outside, I guess?"
Tried rekindling romance with my wife by whispering sweet nothings; turns out she prefers actual conversation.
I told my mirror I was taking it to see a horror movie; it told me it's seen enough scary faces already.
I installed a high-fidelity car stereo; my neighbors love it so much, they threw a brick through my window to hear it better.
The Great Barrier Reef is so popular, even fish are on a waiting list to get in.
I asked my printer for a motivational poster, and it printed a picture of itself with the caption "At least I work sometimes."
Scuba divers are always so calm because they know how to go with the flow, especially around intricate coral formations.
I opened Pandora's box and found it was just full of unanswered emails and expired coupons.
I have a two-way mirror in my house; it's great for reflecting on who's really on the inside.
I went shopping in Milan and came back with a lighter wallet – turns out, window shopping is just as expensive there.
I tried to lower back pain by doing yoga, but now I can't get up from the downward dog.
Start-ups are like Schrödinger's businesses, they simultaneously exist and don't until someone checks their bank account.
I told my friend my garden plot was just like my story – it had too many holes, and nothing was growing.
I tried to print a vegan cookbook, but my printer ran out of edible ink.
I chose my own adventure in the book and ended up with a paper cut; the stakes were higher than I thought.
I asked for a book on treachery and got a map instead – turns out it was full of double-crossings.
PlayStation VR is the only place where you can say you've climbed Everest and fought dragons, and it's not a lie—it's just not the whole truth.
Lazy Katie was asked to do something, and she replied, "I'm already on it – I've scheduled a nap for that."
I asked my stockbroker to explain a dip in the market; he just took me salsa dancing.
I tried to write a novel about gardening, but the plot was too cultivated.
In "The Sons of Katie Elder," Katie's the strong one; the sons just couldn't handle the family group chat.
I tried to walk through a mirror to another world, but I just ended up in a pane.
The PlayStation Network is like my high school reunion—full of people I don't recognize trying to reconnect.
I tried some aged cheese that was so mature, it gave me advice on my 401(k).
I bought a football in Milan and it came with a lifetime achievement award – seems like every ball there is a celebrity.
I tried to get into a Milanese opera, but apparently, "singing in the shower" isn't considered a qualifying performance.
I asked for a senior discount and they gave me a coupon for a free dinosaur.
I got promoted to a subordinate position; now I'm officially under someone else's thumb.
My silk scarf is so gentle, it got offended when I used the term "rough draft."
My pension plan is like a mystery novel – I'm excited to see how it ends, but I'm pretty sure I won't like the twist.
When Katie heard "bar the door," she installed an actual minibar – now that's what I call an open-door policy.
My kitchen appliances are so modern after the installation, they just had a meeting to discuss my cooking skills.
I had a heart attack when I saw my ex's new partner, but it was just heartburn from the vindaloo we had for lunch.
I told José he should try carpentry, but he said he couldn't handle the pressure of living up to his saintly namesake.
I spent hours selecting the perfect font for my party invitations; too bad my friends are all Comic Sans people.
I tried to RSVP to a gala with "regrets only," but apparently, "I'm watching paint dry that evening" wasn't the kind of regret they were looking for.
I invited José for a coffee, but he brought his own beans and called it "Café con José."
My new art exhibition is so contemporary, even the paintings still don't know what they mean.
I'd tell you a chemistry joke but I know I wouldn't get a reaction.
I asked José if he could see the irony in his name being a homophone with the national anthem, but he just stood up and took off his hat.
I asked a philosopher about fundamental questions, and he said, "To be or not to be is not one of them; it's just indecisive."
My friend's bakery burned down last night. Now his business is toast.
I got an Evite that was so stylish, it made my email inbox look underdressed.
I tried to start a recycling program for broken boomerangs, but they just kept coming back.
My therapist recommended self-care, so I took her advice and canceled my next appointment.
I bought a biodegradable watch, but it's a race against time.
My action figure went to a job interview; it was for a role-playing position.
I tried to play a fundamental frequency on my guitar, but it turned out to be just a baseless accusation.
My phone's firmware was so outdated, when I tried to update it, it swiped left on the OTA update.
I told my Lego bricks to assemble themselves; they said they're not part of the Avengers.
I don't trust atoms; they make up everything, even the pollution.
I was going to write a time travel joke, but you guys didn't like it.
I told my friend I knew a great trick to avoid procrastination, but I'll tell him later.
I bought a dental crown made of chocolate; now my smile is both sweet and cavity-inducing!
My internet was so slow, I clicked "download" and it gave me an estimated time of the next Ice Age.
My dog's a magician... every time I open the fridge, he appears out of thin air!
I told my girlfriend she was the beat of my heart; she said she preferred a man with a bit more rhythm.
Toy soldiers are the most disciplined; they've never broken ranks, even when the vacuum attacks.
I installed a custom ROM on my phone, and now it's acting like it's from an alternate universe.
I bought a gentle fabric softener, now my shirts are too timid to meet my pants.
Why don't cells use online dating? Because they believe in division before multiplication.
I'm not an influence on my younger brother; I just told him life's a game and now he's trying to find the cheat codes.
I tried to play a trick on the calendar, but it had a date with destiny.
I downloaded a pirate movie the other day; it came with a parrot that says "You wouldn't download a ship, would you?"
Why don't skeletons fight each other? They don't have the guts.
I tried to follow an algorithm for success, but it turned out to be a loop—now I'm great at déjà vu.
I had a breakthrough in therapy; I realized I could have bought a car with the money I've spent.
I asked a particle physicist to help me with a basic recipe, but all I got was a lecture on fundamental particles.
I wore a crown of thorns to a costume party; it wasn't a hit, but I definitely left an impression.
I downloaded a PDF on procrastination; I'll tell you how it ends later.
Divorce is like algebra – you look at your X and wonder Y.
I tried to update my BIOS, but now my computer just makes sizzling sounds; I guess it's more "fried"ware than firmware.
My genealogy timeline is so boring, even my ancestors fell asleep researching it.
I'm all for validation, so when my GPS says I'm on the fastest route, I feel like I've won an award.
I won a silent auction with a mime; I guess actions speak louder than words.
My friend's an accomplice to my procrastination; he's the one who introduced me to the snooze button.
Tried a gentle yoga class; I was so relaxed, I didn't even mind when I fell asleep and snored.
Data mining sounds like a tough job until you realize it's all done while sitting down with coffee.
I told my friend I tiled my pool with Scrabble tiles; he said, "That's a wordy way to take a dive."
My Mahjong tiles are so beautifully engraved that I'm afraid to play with them; I might ruin their calligraphy career.
I told my friend I'm collecting valuable art; he was impressed until he saw my fridge covered in toddler drawings.
I gave the green light to my diet plan, but it turned yellow at the sight of a donut shop.
A software bug is just a feature that hasn't found its fan base yet.
I told my computer I needed a break, and now it won't stop sending me Kit-Kat ads.
I tried to buy a stealth bomber at the auction, but I couldn't find it.
I installed heated tiles in my house, and now my cat thinks he's a loaf of bread in a slow cooker.
The boxer's bakery failed because every time he made dough, he ended up striking it.
The activist's speech was so moving, even the statues started striking poses.
I told my friend he was the catalyst of the party, and sure enough, he sped up everyone's departure.
I extended an olive branch to my neighbor, but he was more interested in the branch from my apple tree.
I bought a rare vintage wine collection; it's like my financial plan, locked away and never to see daylight.
I'm reading a book on anti-gravity; it's impossible to put down.
I asked my therapist for confidentiality, and she said, "Sure, I'll keep it as quiet as your social life."
I wasn't originally going to get a brain transplant, but then I changed my mind.
I told my cat he was the heir to the throne; now he won't stop sitting on my head like a crown.
I asked a corporation how it stays in shape; it said, "I do lots of little company crunches."
The class system is like a bad yearbook photo – it's all about who's on top and who's a footnote.
I started a timeline of my dieting milestones, but it just ended up looking like a yo-yo string.
I told my contractor to give me a bid on my roof, now it's through the ceiling.
